kernel_variant.question:
Let  n\ge 2  be an integer and let  \mathcal B  be an arbitrary set of  n  distinct real numbers (their particular labels are irrelevant).  Arrange the elements of  \mathcal B  in a row in a uniformly random order.  For a position  k\in\{1,\dots ,n\}  call the element in that position a \emph{valley} if
\[
\begin{cases}
\text{(i)} & k=1\;\text{ and the first element is smaller than the second;}\\[2mm]
\text{(ii)} & 1<k<n\;\text{ and the element is smaller than both its immediate neighbours;}\\[2mm]
\text{(iii)}& k=n\;\text{ and the last element is smaller than the $(n-1)$st.}
\end{cases}
\]
(Thus a valley is a local minimum rather than a local maximum.)  Find the expected number of valleys when the ordering is chosen uniformly at random.
